administration of Mayor Lee Brown was believed to have favored Montgomery=20
Watson's chief competitor, Azurix Corp., an arm of local energy giant Enron=20
Corp.=20
The water corporation, known as "the Hawk," voted 5-0 to grant the contract.=
=20
If approved by City Council, the contract would give the company 2 1/2 years=
=20
to get the plant up and treating raw lake water.=20
It was initially expected that the plant, which will be designed to handle 4=
0=20
million gallons of water daily, could cost as much as $150 million to build.=
=20
The Hawk board asked the vying companies to modify their bids several times,=
=20
and that caused the competitors to lower their prices.=20
The contract calls for the Hawk to pay a monthly operating fee of $157,000=20
when the plant is working. And Montgomery Watson could be required to=20
construct, at the Hawk's option, an additional 40 million-gallon-a-day plant=
=20
expansion for $32 million.=20
But the details of how the plant will be financed have not been determined.=20
The Hawk board discussed borrowing money using the city's credit rating on a=
=20
short-term basis until it could develop long-term financing by selling bonds=
=20
itself.=20
The initial customer for the water is the city of Houston, which would repay=
=20
the Hawk the cost of producing the treated water. The hope is that the plant=
=20
eventually will provide water to other entities in the area as well. This=20
plant is part of an area plan for the treatment of surface water that could=20
cost about $2 billion to implement.=20
City Councilman Carroll Robinson, who heads the council infrastructure=20
committee, said he expects to hold two hearings about the contract. One woul=
d=20
focus on how the Hawk board picked Montgomery Watson. A series of three=20
recommendations from City Hall staff recommended Azurix.=20
Hawk board members said Montgomery Watson's prices were lower by millions an=
d=20
that Azurix plans to sell Azurix North America, the body that would oversee=20
this contract.=20
The second City Council hearing will focus on financing, Robinson said. "In=20
my mind, how the city will pay for this construction is as important as who=20
will do it," Robinson said.=20
The Hawk board, appointed by Brown and approved by City Council, has been=20
heavily lobbied by the contenders for the job.=20
Because City Council does not have to follow the Hawk recommendation, new=20
pressure has begun at City Hall. The third bidder, U.S. Filter Operating=20
Services, part of a French company, has been heavily lobbying some council=20
members to switch the contract to it.=20
Some members of the Azurix team -- people at companies that would have gotte=
n=20
work had Azurix gotten the job -- have written letters complaining about the=
=20
Hawk procedures as well.=20
John M. Stokes, president and chief executive officer of Azurix, penned the=20
first such distressed missive. In April, he wrote to Hawk board Chairman=20
David Berg complaining of the "deleterious economic effect" on Azurix of the=
=20
board's decision to negotiate with Montgomery Watson. He requested that Berg=
=20
answer a series of questions in writing explaining why Azurix didn't get the=
=20
job. Berg didn't do so.=20
Although that letter had a threatening tone, Amanda Martin, president of=20
Azurix North America, said no threat was intended and the letter simply=20
indicated how upset the team was when it first learned Azurix wasn't chosen.=
=20
Azurix was the rumored front-runner for months.=20


