TOKYO, May 15 (Reuters) - A senior executive of U.S. energy giant Enron Corp=
=20
said on Tuesday that Japan could save an estimated four trillion yen ($32.45=
=20
billion) in annual costs if electricity rates were cut to the average of=20
members of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).=
=20
"If you were to pare Japanese industrial electric rates to the OECD=20
average...savings to all...customers would be about four trillion yen per=20
year," Enron Corp Vice President Steven Kean told a seminar in Tokyo.
Speaking at a seminar on electric power deregulation, Kean said that=20
indigenous factors such as steep land prices and a lack of natural energy=20
resources were often blamed for Japan's high electricity rates.=20
But he said these factors were not sufficient to explain Japan's high=20
electricity rates.=20
A report commissioned by Enron Japan Corp showed that in 1998 Japan's=20
electricity rates for industrial users were 16.81 yen per kilowatt hour (kWh=
)=20
compared to a second highest rate of 12.44 yen in Italy.=20
Japan's business sector has expressed concern at the nation's high=20
electricity rates, saying that it blunts their competitive edge on the=20
international market.=20
Kean also drew parallels between Japan, in the midst of deregulation, and=20
California which has been suffering from a power shortage since deregulating=
=20
its market in 1998.=20
These included the length of time that authorities in Japan took to issue=20
permits to allow the construction of new power plants, he said.=20
"The regulatory structure in Japan is very strict...just like in California,=
"=20
Kean said.=20
North America's biggest buyer and seller of electricity, Enron gained its=20
first foothold in Japan in 1999 when it established affiliate E Power Corp.=20
In April of last year, it set up subsidiary Enron Japan Corp.=20
Kean urged Japan to step up measures to open up its power market, a process=20
he said held many benefits.=20
Japan is in the process of deregulating its power market. Since March last=20
year, large-lot consumers have been free to chose their suppliers. The=20
measure liberalised an estimated 30 percent of the power market and ended=20
Japan's 10 power utilities regional monopoly.=20
However, industry watchers note that there have been very few new entrants=20
and that further deregulation measures must be taken for rates to fall. The=20
Japanese government is due to review the process in 2003.

